   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse        = Jennifer Letulle\n|children      = 2\n|alma_mater    = [[Louisiana State University|Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}\n|website       = {{url|scalise.house.gov|House website}}<br>{{url|majoritywhip.house.gov|Party website}}\n}}\n'''Stephen Joseph''' \"'''Steve'''\" '''Scalise''' (born October 6, 1965) is the current [[United States House of Representatives]] Majority Whip and representative for {{ushr|LA|1}}, serving since 2008. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/floorsummary/floor.html?day=20080410&today=20080410 |title=Current House Floor Proceedings Legislative Day of May 7, 2008 110th Congress \u2013 Second Session |publisher=Clerk.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/new.html |title=Office of the clerk, U.S. House of Representative |publisher=Clerk.house.gov |date=2008-05-07 |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref> and was the chairman of the [[Conservative (politics)|conservative]] House [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shreveporttimes.com/article/20130819/NEWS01/308190010/With-Alexander-departing-delegation-s-clout-question|title=Deborah Barfield Berry, With Alexander departing, delegation's clout in question? Will Alexander loss, Senate battle hurt Louisiana in the nation's capital?|publisher=''[[The Times (Shreveport)|Shreveport Times]]''|accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nPrior to his congressional tenure, Scalise served for four months in the [[Louisiana State Senate]] and twelve years in the [[Louisiana House of Representatives]]. On June 19, 2014, Scalise was elected by his Republican colleagues to serve as [[Majority Whip of the United States House of Representatives]]. He assumed office on August 1. He is the first Louisianan in the Majority Whip's position since [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Hale Boggs]] of [[Louisiana's 2nd congressional district]] held the position from 1962 to 1971.\n\n==Early life==\nScalise was born in New Orleans, one of three children of Alfred Joseph Scalise, a [[real estate broker]] who died on October 8, 2015 at the age of seventy-seven, and the former Carol Schilleci. His siblings are Glenn and Tara Scalise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://obits.nola.com/obituaries/nola/obituary.aspx?n=alfred-joseph-scalise&pid=176066622|title=Alfred Joseph Scalise|publisher=''[[New Orleans Times-Picayune]]''|date=October 9, 2015|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nScalise graduated from [[Archbishop Rummel High School]] in [[Metairie, Louisiana|Metairie]] in [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]] and earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[Louisiana State University]] in [[Baton Rouge]], with a major in [[computer programming]] and a minor in [[political science]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pierce|first1=Charles|title=Home / Blogs / The Politics Blog The Politics Blog The Republicans' New Debt Ceiling \"Menu\"|url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/paul-ryan-debt-ceiling-menu-070813|accessdate=8 December 2014|publisher=Esquire|date=July 8, 2013}}</ref> At [[Louisiana State University]], Scalise was a [[List of Acacia brothers|member]] of the [[Acacia (fraternity)|Acacia Fraternity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gawker.com/tell-us-about-your-fraternitys-racist-history-and-or-pr-1691338200|title=Tell Us About Your Fraternity's Racist History and/or Present|publisher=''[[Gawker]]''|date=March 16, 2015|accessdate=September 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Louisiana Legislature==\nAfter Republican State Representative [[Quentin Dastugue|Quentin D. Dastugue]] made an unsuccessful bid for [[Governor of Louisiana]] in the 1995 Republican primary, Scalise was recruited by state Republicans to run for his seat in the [[Louisiana House of Representatives]], which he did, winning election to it in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/05/steve-scalise-take-two-117642_Page2.html#.VgHk20bi_8d|title=Steve Scalise, Take Two|publisher=''[[Politico]]''|last=Bridges|first=Tyler|date=May 7, 2015|accessdate=September 22, 2015}}</ref> Scalise was re-elected to the seat in 1995 and 1999, serving until 2003.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=27339 Scalise, Steve J.] {{wayback|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=27339 |date=20160304090104 }} ourcampaigns.com. Retrieved September 22, 2015.</ref>\nHis legislative peers named him to the House Appropriations Committee as the representative of the First Congressional District. Scalise opposed the 2002 [[Stelly Plan]], a proposal by [[Lake Charles, Louisiana|Lake Charles]] Representative [[Vic Stelly]], since [[repeal]]ed, to reduce certain [[state sales tax]]es on food for home consumption and utilities in exchange for higher [[state income tax]]es.\n\nScalise was elected in the October 20, 2007, [[jungle primary|nonpartisan blanket primary]] to the District 9 seat in the [[Louisiana Senate]] vacated by the term-limited [[Ken Hollis]] of [[Metairie, Louisiana|Metairie]]. Scalise received 19,154 votes (61 percent) in a three-way contest. Fellow Republican Polly Thomas polled 8,948 votes (29 percent). A Democrat, David Gereighty, polled 3,154 votes (10 percent) in the heavily Republican-oriented district. Scalise was succeeded in the state House by his aide, [[Cameron Henry]] of [[Metairie, Louisiana|Metairie]].\n\nIn the special election on November 4, 2008 to fill the remaining three and one-half years in Scalise's state Senate term, [[Conrad Appel]] defeated Polly Thomas, 21,853 (52.1 percent) to 20,065 (47.9 percent). Thomas had also lost the race for the seat in 2007 to Scalise.<ref>Louisiana Secretary of State, November 4, 2008, election results: {{cite web|url=http://www400.sos.louisiana.gov:8090/cgibin/?rqstyp%3Delcms3%26rqsdta%3D110408 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-08 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081128141036/http://www400.sos.louisiana.gov:8090/cgibin/?rqstyp=elcms3&rqsdta=110408 |archivedate=November 28, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\nOn being asked by the ''[[New Orleans Times-Picayune]]'' to assign [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Barack Obama]] a letter grade for Obama's first 100 days as [[President of the United States|President]], Scalise awarded the new president an ''L'' (for \"[[Modern liberalism in the United States#\"Liberal\" as a derogatory epithet|liberal]]\").<ref>Tilove, Jonathan, \"Obama's first 100 days are graded on a curve\" in ''Times-Picayune'' (New Orleans), 2009 April 29, Saint Tammany Edition, pp. A1, A6 (web version =  [http://www.nola.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/louisianas_congressional_deleg.html Louisiana's congressional delegation grades President Obama's first 100 days from A to L.)]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|Subcommittee on Communications and Technology]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n===Legislative history===\nIn 2011, Scalise became a co-sponsor of Bill H.R.3261 otherwise known as the [[Stop Online Piracy Act]] (withdrawn Jan 23, 2012).<ref name=\"govtrack\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-3261 Bill H.R.3261] {{wayback|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-3261 |date=20120316212131 }}; GovTrack.us;</ref> As chairman of the Republican Study Committee, Scalise dismissed [[Derek Khanna]], a committee staffer, in December 2012 because of pressure from content industry lobbyists after the study committee published a memo advocating [[copyright]] reform.<ref>{{cite news | first = Timothy B. | last = Lee | title = Staffer axed by Republican group over retracted copyright-reform memo | date = December 6, 2012 | publisher = [[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]] | url = http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2012/12/staffer-axed-by-republican-group-over-retracted-copyright-reform-memo/ | work = [[Ars Technica]] | accessdate = December 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Scalise voted against reauthorizing the [[Violence Against Women Act]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Trotter|first=J.K.|title=Here's Who Voted Against the Violence Against Women Act|url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/politics/2013/02/heres-who-voted-against-violence-against-women-act/62633/|newspaper=The Atlantic|date=February 28, 2013}}</ref> Also in 2013, Scalise sponsored a bill called the FCC Consolidated Reporting Act. The bill makes the [[Federal Communications Commission (FCC)]] consolidate several of their reports into one report.<ref>Harrison, Julie, [http://riponadvance.com/news/scalises-fcc-consolidation-bill-sails-through-house/4712 \"Scalise\u2019s FCC consolidation bill sails through House\"] {{wayback|url=http://riponadvance.com/news/scalises-fcc-consolidation-bill-sails-through-house/4712 |date=20150105132235 }}, ''The Ripon Advance'', 9-12-13. (Retrieved 9-12-13).</ref>\n\n===Leadership race===\nIn the aftermath of Rep. [[Eric Cantor]]'s unexpected defeat by [[David Brat]] on June 10, 2014, Scalise launched a campaign to replace Rep. [[Kevin McCarthy (California politician)|Kevin McCarthy]] in the position of [[Majority Whip]] of the House; McCarthy himself would replace Cantor as House Majority Leader. Scalise's ascent to leadership built on his \"come-from-behind win in 2012 to become chairman\" of the [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>Joachim, David S., [http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/us/politics/steve-scalise-of-louisiana-gets-lift-from-fellow-southern-lawmakers.html \"Louisianan Seeks to Extend Rapid Rise in House G.O.P.\"] {{wayback|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/us/politics/steve-scalise-of-louisiana-gets-lift-from-fellow-southern-lawmakers.html |date=20151109052513 }}, New York ''Times'', June 19, 2014. Retrieved 2014-06-19.</ref> Scalise subsequently won a three-way race for whip, winning on the first ballot despite the efforts of fellow candidates [[Peter Roskam]] and [[Marlin Stutzman]].<ref>Parker, Ashley, and Jeremy W. Peters, [http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/us/kevin-mccarthy-elected-house-majority-leader.html \"House Republicans Name McCarthy as Cantor\u2019s Replacement\"] {{wayback|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/us/kevin-mccarthy-elected-house-majority-leader.html |date=20151001072949 }}, New York ''Times'', June 19, 2014. Retrieved 2014-06-19.</ref><ref name=JSherman>{{cite news|last1=Sherman|first1=Jake|last2=Bresnahan|first2=John|last3=Palmer|first3=Anna|title=Inside the House GOP leadership shake-up|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/06/inside-the-house-gop-leadership-shake-up-108103.html?hp=f2|accessdate=20 June 2014|publisher=Politico|date=19 June 2014}}</ref> He came under fire for using the assistance of a federal lobbyist, John Feehery, when hiring staff for the Majority Leader's Press Office.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Palmer|first1=Anna|last2=Sherman|first2=Jake|title=To pick staff, Scalise turns to lobbyist|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/08/steve-scalise-staff-john-feehery-109739.html?hp=t1_3|website=www.politico.com|publisher=Politico|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince becoming Majority Whip, Scalise has delivered several public defeats for the GOP on immigration, abortion, and education policy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/the-gop-s-lost-agenda-20150303 |title=The GOP's Lost Agenda |last1=Newhauser |first1=Daniel |date=3 March 2015 |website=nationaljournal.com |publisher=National Journal Group Inc. |accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\n\n===2008 special election===\n{{main article|Louisiana's 1st congressional district special election, 2008}}\nIn 2004, Scalise announced that he would run for the U.S. House but thereafter deferred to the preference of party leaders and supported Jindal, who won the position vacated by the successful U.S. senatorial candidate, [[David Vitter]].\n\nIn 2007, when Jindal was elected to the governorship of Louisiana, Scalise announced his intentions to seek the seat yet again. This time he received Republican party backing.\n\nScalise's strongest Republican primary opponent, [[Louisiana State Legislature|State Representative]] [[Timothy Burns (Louisiana politician)|Timothy G. \"Tim\" Burns]] from [[Mandeville, Louisiana|Mandeville]] in [[St. Tammany Parish]], accused Scalise of [[push polling]], a practice in which a campaign contacts voters by telephone and asks probing questions which leave a negative impression of his opponent. Scalise defended his poll from criticism by Burns: \"We were running a public opinion survey this week conducted by the largest Republican polling firm in the country, Public Opinion Strategies. . . . conducted with a sample of 300 people, and it shows Scalise at 57 percent, Burns at 26 percent and undecided at 17 percent The margin of error is 5.6 percent. We ran a fact-based public opinion survey, not a push poll.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nola.com/news/t-p/capital/index.ssf?/base/news-5/1205560202224150.xml&coll=1 |title=Scalise defends integrity of GOP runoff survey |publisher=NOLA.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref>\n\nIn the March 8, 2008, Republican primary, Scalise polled 16,799 votes (48 percent). He went on to win the [[runoff election]] on April 5 against Burns, who received 9,631 votes (28 percent) in the initial primary.<ref name=\"Runoff\"/><ref name=\"Runoff\">[http://electionresults.sos.louisiana.gov/040508state.htm Louisiana Secretary of State Unofficial Election Results Inquiry Results for Election Date: 4/05/08]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nola.com/ |title='''nola.com''' ELECTIONS section |publisher=Nola.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref>\n\nIn the May 3 general election, Scalise received 33,867 votes (75.13 percent) to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Gilda Reed's 10,142 ballots (22.5 percent). Two minor candidates polled the remaining 2.36 percent of the vote. Reed was a favorite of [[organized labor]] and the Democratic constituency groups. The First District has been Republican since 1977, when [[Bob Livingston]] won a special election.<ref>[http://www400.sos.louisiana.gov:8090/cgibin/?rqstyp=elcms2&rqsdta=050308 Louisiana Secretary of State-Multi-Parish Elections Inquiry<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{wayback|url=http://www400.sos.louisiana.gov:8090/cgibin/?rqstyp=elcms2&rqsdta=050308 |date=20080919002739 }}</ref>\n\nScalise was sworn in on May 7, 2008.\n\n===2008===\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Louisiana, 2008#District 1}}\nIn the regularly scheduled election, Scalise was reelected over Democrat Jim Harlan, 66 percent to 34 percent.\n\n===2010===\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Louisiana, 2010#District 1}}\nScalise defeated the Democratic nominee, Myron Katz, and an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]], Arden Wells, in his 2010 bid for reelection.\n\n===2012===\nIn June 2009, Scalise joined [[Dan Kyle]], the former legislative auditor and the treasurer of the Louisiana GOP, as directors of a national [[U.S. President|presidential]] fund-raising effort promoting Governor Jindal. According to Kyle, the group hoped to raise $60 million to persuade Jindal to seek the 2012 party nomination.<ref name=jindal>{{cite web|url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/48123092.html|title=Michelle Millhollon, \"Official pulls out of Jindal group\", June 16, 2009|publisher=''[[The Advocate (Baton Rouge)|Baton Rouge Morning Advocate]]''|accessdate=November 23, 2009}}</ref> Others on the committee include former State Representative [[Woody Jenkins]]. Former Republican [[Louisiana State Legislature|State Senator]] [[Tom Schedler]] of [[Slidell, Louisiana|Slidell]] had his name removed from the group, not because he opposes Jindal but because such fund-raising activity could conflict with Schedler's role at the time as first assistant to Louisiana Secretary of State [[Jay Dardenne]].<ref name=jindal/> In 2010, Schedler succeeded Dardenne as secretary of state.\n\nIn his own 2012 congressional race, Scalise prevailed with 193,490 votes (66.6 percent) over four opponents, the strongest of which was the Democrat M. V. \"Vinny\" Mendoza, who finished with 61,979 votes (21.3 percent). A second Republican, Gary King, received 24,838 votes (8.6 percent). Independent Arden Wells ran again and received 4,285 votes (1.5 percent) in his second race against Scalise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/11062012/11062012_Congressional.html|title=Louisiana election returns, November 6, 2012|publisher=staticresults.sos.la.gov|accessdate=November 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==European-American Unity and Rights Organization speech==\nIn 2014, political blogger<ref name=Costa-141229 /><ref name=Martin /> [[Lamar White|Lamar White, Jr.]] uncovered anonymous comments from 2002 on the white supremacist website [[Stormfront (website)|Stormfront]] that referenced a speech Scalise had given, from which he concluded Scalise addressed the [[European-American Unity and Rights Organization]] (EURO), a group founded by [[David Duke]].<ref name=Costa-141229>{{cite web | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/house-majority-whip-scalise-confirms-he-spoke-to-white-nationalists-in-2002/2014/12/29/7f80dc14-8fa3-11e4-a900-9960214d4cd7_story.html | title=House Majority Whip Scalise confirms he spoke to white nationalists in 2002 | work=Washington Post | accessdate=29 December 2014 | author=Costa, Robert}}</ref><ref name=Jaffe>{{cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/12/29/politics/steve-scalise-white-supremacist-group-speech/ | title=GOP leadership stands by Scalise after white supremacist speech | work=CNN | date=December 31, 2014 | accessdate=December 31, 2014 |author1=Jaffe, Alexandra  |author2=Walsh, Deirdra |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref name=Sarlin>{{cite web | url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/gop-leader-steve-scalise-may-have-addressed-supremacist-rally | title=GOP leader Steve Scalise may have addressed supremacist conference | work=MSNBC | date=December 29, 2014 | accessdate=December 29, 2014 | author=Sarlin, Benjy}}</ref><ref name=\"Reilly\">{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/29/steve-scalise-euro-conference_n_6392036.html | title=House Majority Whip Steve Scalise Spoke At White Supremacist Conference In 2002 | work=The Huffington Post | date=December 29, 2014 | accessdate=December 29, 2014 |author1=Reilly, Mollie  |author2=Grim, Ryan |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cenlamar.com/2014/12/28/house-majority-whip-steve-scalise-was-reportedly-an-honored-guest-at-2002-international-white-supremacist-convention/|title=House Majority Whip Steve Scalise Was Reportedly an Honored Guest at 2002 International White Supremacist Convention|publisher=|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=Calderone>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/30/lamar-white-jr-scalise-blogger_n_6397078.html | title=How Louisiana Blogger Lamar White, Jr. Landed The Steve Scalise White Supremacist Scoop | work=[[Huffington Post]] | date=December 30, 2014 | accessdate=December 31, 2014 | author=Calderone, Michael}}</ref> White posted his findings on his blog and soon after the media took note. Scalise said that he had spoken at the conference in 2002 and stated that he did not know of the \"racist nature of the group\".<ref name=Martin>{{cite web | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/31/us/politics/scalises-speech-to-white-supremacist-group-clouds-republicans-plans.html | title=Republicans Try to Fix Damage Scalise\u2019s 2002 Speech Could Do in 2016 | work=[[New York Times]] | date=December 31, 2014 | accessdate=December 31, 2014 |author1=Martin, jonathan  |author2=Calmes, Jackie |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\nVarious Louisiana politicians, including Republican Governor [[Bobby Jindal]] and Democratic Congressman [[Cedric Richmond]] defended Scalise's character.<ref name=ODonoghue>{{cite web | url=http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/12/steve_scalise_white_supremacis.html | title=Steve Scalise attended white nationalist event, but says he wasn't aware of group's views | work=The Times-Picayune | date=December 29, 2014 | accessdate=December 29, 2014 | author=O'Donoghue, Julia}}</ref> [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[John Boehner]] voiced his continued confidence in Scalise as Majority Whip.<ref name=Jaffe /><ref name=Bendery>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/30/john-boehner-steve-scalise_n_6396798.html | title=John Boehner Backs Steve Scalise Amid Controversy Over White Supremacist Meeting | work=[[Huffington Post]] | date=December 30, 2014 | accessdate=December 31, 2014 | author=Bendery, Jennifer}}</ref> Several Democratic members of Congress, as well as [[Mo Elleithee]], a spokesperson for the Democratic National Committee, criticized Scalise, and challenged his statement that he was not aware of the group's affiliation with racism and anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/democrats-demand-answers-steve-scalises-ties-david-duke|title=Steve Scalise: Speaking at supremacist event 'a mistake I regret'|author=Benjy Sarlin|date=March 19, 2015|work=MSNBC}}</ref> Mark Potok of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] called upon Scalise to step down from his leadership position as Majority Whip.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://splcenter.org/blog/2014/12/30/steve-scalises-denials-are-not-believable/|title=Southern Poverty Law Center|work=Southern Poverty Law Center}}</ref><ref name=Berman>{{cite web | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2014/12/30/splc-calls-for-congressman-who-spoke-to-white-supremacist-group-to-step-down-from-leadership/ | title=SPLC calls for congressman who spoke to white supremacist group to step down from leadership | work=[[Washington Post]] | date=December 30, 2014 | accessdate=December 31, 2014 | author=Berman, Mark}}</ref> According to John Hayward at [[Human Events]], the story of Scalise's speaking engagement in 2002 was \"either dubiously sourced, a mistake, or an outright hoax\".<ref name=Hayward>{{cite web | url=http://humanevents.com/2014/12/31/media-um-that-big-steve-scalise-story-probably-didnt-happen/ | title=Media: Um, that big Steve Scalise story probably didn\u2019t happen, but he\u2019s still \u2018embattled\u2019 anyway | work=[[Human Events]] | date=December 31, 2014 | accessdate=December 31, 2014 | author=Hayward, John}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.foxnews.com/2014/12/31/media-um-big-steve-scalise-story-probably-didnt-happen-hes-still-embattled-anyway|title=Media: Um, That Big Steve Scalise Story Probably Didn't Happen, But He's Still 'Embattled' Anyway|work=FoxNation.com}}</ref>\n\nOn December 29, Niels Lesniewski of ''[[Roll Call]]'' reprinted an article that had been run in 1999, after Congressman [[Bob Livingston]] had resigned from Congress. Duke and Scalise were considering running for his seat and they and others were interviewed for the piece. When asked about a potential bid for Congress by Duke, Scalise had told the newspaper that he held many of the same conservative views as Duke, but was a more electable candidate, saying that Duke's novelty had worn off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/218/scalise-vitter-talked-to-roll-call-about-david-duke-in-1999/|title=What Scalise and Vitter Told Roll Call About David Duke in 1999|work=Roll Call|author=Niels Lesniewski|date=December 29, 2014|accessdate=December 31, 2014}}</ref>  Duke called Scalise a \"sellout\" for apologizing for speaking to the group and said that he might run against him in the 2016 elections because Scalise had been \"elected on false pretenses\" and had \"betrayed\" the voters by \"suggesting that they're racist because they supported my views\".<ref name=mightchallenge>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/01/david-duke-steve-scalise-114736.html|title=David Duke says he \u2018might\u2019 challenge Rep. Steve Scalise|work=Politico|date=January 29, 2015|accessdate=January 30, 2015|author=Kendall Breitman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/andrewkaczynski/david-duke-says-he-might-run-for-congress-against-sell-out-s|title=David Duke Says He Might Run For Congress Against \"Sell Out\" Steve Scalise|work=BuzzFeed|date=January 29, 2015|accessdate=January 30, 2015|author1=Andrew Kaczynski|author2=Megan Apper}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/01/29/david-duke-steve-scalise_n_6575792.html|title=Former KKK Leader David Duke Says He May Run Against Steve Scalise|work=The Huffington Post|date=January 29, 2015|accessdate=January 30, 2015|author=Sam Levine}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is a member of the American [[Italy|Italian]] Renaissance Foundation. He married Jennifer Ann Scalise nee Letulle (born 1975) on September 4, 2005.<ref name=marriageannouncement1>{{cite news|title=Marriage Annacouments|url=http://files.usgwarchives.net/la/orleans/vitals/marriages/paper/tp-s.txt|accessdate=31 December 2014|publisher=Times Picayune|date=2006}}</ref> The couple has two children.<ref>Alpert, Bruce, [http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/06/steve_scalise_wins_house_lead.html \"You can call him 'Mr. Majority Whip' \u2013 Rep. Steve Scalise wins House leadership race\"]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }},\n